and history using exact
replicas; self-made

22:21.840 --> 22:25.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
myth -- a millionaire reflects
on the help
he got that goes unacknowledged.

22:26.044 --> 22:32.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: The U.S. Supreme
Court's final
case this term was expected to
be a highly

22:33.085 --> 22:38.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
technical argument on
immigration law, but
it wound up pulling back the
curtain a little

22:38.523 --> 22:42.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the justices' personalities,
and how they
interact with each other.

22:42.661 --> 22:46.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
John Yang has the details of
listening in
on court arguments.

22:46.164 --> 22:50.635 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Here to walk us
through some of
the key moments during
Wednesday's oral arguments

22:50.736 --> 22:52.304 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
is Robert Barnes.

22:52.404 --> 22:56.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He has covered the Supreme Court
for The Washington
Post for more than a decade.

22:56.208 --> 22:58.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he also had the misfortune
of being my
editor at The Post.

22:58.543 --> 22:59.444 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

22:59.544 --> 23:00.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But, Bob, thanks for
coming in.

23:00.912 --> 23:02.147 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT BARNES, The Washington
Post: It's good
to be here.

23:02.247 --> 23:04.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: In a nutshell, Bob,
what was this
case about?

23:04.182 --> 23:09.588 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT BARNES: Well, this is a
case about
a woman from Bosnia who claimed
persecution,

23:09.688 --> 23:14.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
was admitted to this country,
became a naturalized
citizen.

23:14.693 --> 23:18.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then it turned out she had
lied on some
of her applications.

23:18.163 --> 23:22.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Specifically, she had said that
her husband
was trying to avoid military
service.

23:23.001 --> 23:30.175 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It turned out he had been in a
Bosnian militia
unit that had been charged with
some war crimes.

23:30.275 --> 23:35.347 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And the woman's
attorney went first,
since she's the petitioner in
this case.

23:35.447 --> 23:37.249 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How did that argument go?

23:37.349 --> 23:41.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT BARNES: The real fact
here was, does
it matter if something you lie
about on your

23:41.987 --> 23:46.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
application is material to the
fact that you
got citizenship?

23:46.992 --> 23:49.127 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the law is not specific
about that.

23:49.227 --> 23:51.963 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It doesn't say that it has to be
relevant.

23:52.063 --> 23:54.232 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It says that you can't lie.

23:54.332 --> 24:00.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so the government had taken
the position
that any lie would be reason for
it to move

24:00.138 --> 24:04.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
against someone to take away
their citizenship
if they want.

24:04.309 --> 24:08.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the lower courts agreed,
said that, no,
the federal government doesn't
have to prove

24:09.014 --> 24:12.484 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that it was relevant to her
getting it, just
that she had lied.

24:12.584 --> 24:16.988 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so the question for the
court was, is
that the right thing or not?

24:17.088 --> 24:19.090 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is that the right standard?

24:19.191 --> 24:22.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And then, as you
wrote in The Washington
Post, things got really
interesting when they

24:22.627 --> 24:25.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
turned to the government's
attorney, Robert
Parker.

24:25.864 --> 24:28.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Chief Justice John Roberts made
a personal
confession.

24:28.467 --> 24:32.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN ROBERTS, Chief Justice of
the U.S. Supreme
Court: Some time ago, outside
the statute

24:32.471 --> 24:35.507 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of limitations, I drove 60 miles
an hour in
a 55-mile-an-hour zone.

24:35.607 --> 24:37.008 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

24:37.108 --> 24:39.711 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ROBERT PARKER, Justice
Department Attorney:
I'm sorry to hear that.

24:39.811 --> 24:44.182 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN ROBERTS: I wasn't arrested.

24:44.282 --> 24:51.022 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, you say if that I answer
that question
no, 20 years after I was
naturalized as a

24:51.122 --> 24:54.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
citizen, you can knock on my
door and say,
guess what, you're not an
American citizen

24:54.226 --> 24:56.061 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
after all.

24:56.161 --> 25:00.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT BARNES: Well, the chief
justice wasn't
comparing speeding to a war
crime, but what

25:00.665 --> 25:03.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he was saying is, what's the
logical extension
of this?

25:03.668 --> 25:09.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If the government says that
someone can lose
their citizenship for lying
about anything,

25:09.808 --> 25:12.344 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
then how far does that go?

25:12.444 --> 25:17.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does it go to even something as
mundane as
speeding which you didn't fess
up?

25:17.883 --> 25:23.154 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And he had not said
anything in
the arguments with the woman's
attorney; is

25:23.255 --> 25:24.155 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that right?

25:24.256 --> 25:25.891 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROBERT BARNES: That's right.

25:25.991 --> 25:28.693 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Sometimes, when the chief
justice is quiet
during one part of the argument,
if you're

25:28.793 --> 25:33.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the lawyer getting up, you need
to be worried,
because it means that he may
agree with that

25:34.032 --> 25:36.535 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
side and he's ready to pounce on
you.

25:36.635 --> 25:39.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's pretty much what the
chief justice
did to this poor government
lawyer.

25:39.971 --> 25:44.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And then on that
point of what's
relevant and what's not
relevant, there was

25:44.109 --> 25:47.679 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an exchange involving Justice
Elena Kagan.

25:47.779 --> 25:49.114 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, let's take a listen to that.

25:49.214 --> 25:53.952 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT PARKER: I mean, you could
lie about
your weight, let's say.

25:54.052 --> 25:58.089 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You're embarrassed that you
weigh 170 pounds,
and so you claim that you weigh
150.

25:58.189 --> 26:02.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, remember, this has to be a
lie under
oath after you have sworn to
tell the truth,

26:02.794 --> 26:05.597 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and you're deliberately lying
about something.

26:05.697 --> 26:08.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It calls into question the
veracity of your
other answers.

26:08.500 --> 26:10.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that is very important in
the naturalization
process.

26:11.036 --> 26:11.937 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

26:12.037 --> 26:12.938 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT PARKER: I'm sorry.

26:13.038 --> 26:14.873 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Go ahead.

26:14.973 --> 26:15.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELENA KAGAN, Associate Justice,
U.S. Supreme
Court: You will be glad to know
I don't have

26:15.874 --> 26:17.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
another of these questions for
you.

26:17.409 --> 26:19.311 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

26:19.411 --> 26:22.280 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELENA KAGAN: Although I am a
little bit horrified
to know that every time I lie
about my weight,

26:22.380 --> 26:23.949 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it has those kinds of
consequences.

26:24.049 --> 26:24.950 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

26:25.050 --> 26:27.419 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROBERT PARKER: Only under oath.

26:27.519 --> 26:29.321 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
ELENA KAGAN: Yes.

26:29.421 --> 26:32.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: We should point out
that Parker
wasn't referring specifically to
Justice Kagan.

26:32.857 --> 26:33.758 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

26:33.858 --> 26:35.260 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROBERT BARNES: That's right,
exactly right.

26:35.360 --> 26:37.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No, again, it was the same
point.

26:37.929 --> 26:42.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what justices like to do is,
they keep
spinning these ideas out.

26:42.467 --> 26:45.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What about this, what about
this, what about
this?

26:45.437 --> 26:50.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if it's the lawyer in a
position where
they have got to defend
something -- you know,

26:50.208 --> 26:54.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we should point out too, this is
a long-held
government view.

26:54.112 --> 27:00.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not one that has come up
just recently,
but one that has come up a long
time ago.

27:00.552 --> 27:02.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's just that this case got to
the court
now.

27:02.487 --> 27:07.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And then, later in
the arguments,
Justice Anthony Kennedy pressed
Parker about

27:07.859 --> 27:09.628 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the meaning of citizenship.

27:09.728 --> 27:16.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBERT PARKER: All I can say is,
I don't think
that the statute says anything
that would

27:16.134 --> 27:19.804 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
necessarily prevent
denaturalization from
occurring.

27:19.904 --> 27:21.806 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But there are a number of...

27:21.906 --> 27:22.841 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTHONY KENNEDY, Associate
Justice, U.S. Supreme
Court: It seems to me that your
argument is

27:22.941 --> 27:27.245 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
demeaning the priceless value of
citizenship.

27:27.345 --> 27:34.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To say, oh, he would just be
restored to his
-- or she to her former status,
that's not

27:34.119 --> 27:35.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
what our cases say.

27:35.487 --> 27:37.255 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's not what citizenship
means.

27:37.355 --> 27:42.160 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
You're arguing for the
government of the United
States, talking about what
citizenship is

27:42.260 --> 27:44.029 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and ought to mean.

27:44.129 --> 27:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Now you say that
that's a very
characteristic question from
Justice Kennedy.

27:48.466 --> 27:50.335 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROBERT BARNES: Yes.

27:50.435 --> 27:54.839 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
It's bad for your side if
Justice Kennedy
starts talking about something
that the government

27:54.939 --> 28:00.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
does as being demeaning or
affecting the dignity
of an individual, because that's
something

28:00.845 --> 28:03.081 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that's very important to him.

28:03.181 --> 28:07.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And those are words that no
lawyer really
wants to hear coming from
Justice Kennedy.

28:07.719 --> 28:10.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Very unusual tone, it
seemed, in
this argument.

28:11.089 --> 28:13.058 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
How usual or unusual is that?

28:13.158 --> 28:17.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROBERT BARNES: This was a very
lively back
and forth among the justices.

28:17.762 --> 28:21.032 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It was a very sort of
entertaining argument
to be at.

28:21.132 --> 28:24.903 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was also their last argument
of the term.

28:25.003 --> 28:31.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After this, the justices start
writing their
opinions in all the cases they
have heard

28:31.309 --> 28:32.644 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
since October.

28:32.744 --> 28:37.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so, in a way, it was sort of
the end of
the school day for them.

28:37.682 --> 28:41.886 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so it was a very interesting
and lively
conversation.

28:41.986 --> 28:46.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Bob Barnes, thanks
for taking us
behind the scenes a little bit
at the Supreme

28:46.791 --> 28:48.393 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Court.

28:48.493 --> 28:55.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROBERT BARNES: My pleasure.

28:55.133 --> 29:00.972 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now to the
