think that's a good move.

37:42.760 --> 37:44.462 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

37:44.562 --> 37:47.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: And so -- and then
the final
thing I will say, I'm really
struck by Bob

37:47.265 --> 37:49.000 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Costa.

37:49.100 --> 37:50.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our colleague from "Washington
Week did a
great -- with Ashley Parker, a
great piece

37:50.635 --> 37:52.436 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on his television watching
habits.

37:52.536 --> 37:56.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he had this interview with
AP where he
talked about how hard it was to
rip himself

37:56.107 --> 38:00.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
away from the habit of watching
every single
TV show about himself.

38:00.478 --> 38:04.749 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so you see a guy sort of
transparently
and naively struggling certainly
with maybe

38:04.849 --> 38:07.418 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
narcissism, but certainly the TV
obsession.

38:07.518 --> 38:11.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the lack of attention span
is what causes
all this fickleness.

38:11.922 --> 38:15.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Whoever saw him last gets the
policy for the
day.

38:15.359 --> 38:18.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And will that settle down, or
will we just
sort of get a weather vane for
the next four

38:18.896 --> 38:20.197 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
years?

38:20.298 --> 38:21.432 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I don't know.

38:21.532 --> 38:25.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I do think that the first 30
days was
unsustainable.

38:25.202 --> 38:27.038 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He was crashing every hour.

38:27.138 --> 38:28.272 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's calmed down a little.

38:28.372 --> 38:30.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: I stand in awe of
David's optimism.

38:30.875 --> 38:31.776 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
I do.

38:31.876 --> 38:32.843 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I really do.

38:32.943 --> 38:33.778 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Fickle better
than dangerous.

38:33.878 --> 38:35.680 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: And, no, I
appreciate it.

38:35.780 --> 38:38.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, Judy, two things have
occurred under
Donald Trump, and Donald Trump
deserves credit

38:38.582 --> 38:40.318 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for.

38:40.418 --> 38:44.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For the first time since it
passed in 2010,
the Affordable Care Act,
Obamacare, is now

38:44.822 --> 38:48.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
more popular than it's ever been
before, a
majority of Americans.

38:48.492 --> 38:52.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's more popular than Donald
Trump, if you
want to do it just on a
comparative.

38:53.030 --> 38:58.402 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the other thing is that
Americans who
had been on a Tea Party tear for
smaller government

38:58.502 --> 39:02.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now government, according to a
Wall Street
Journal/NBC poll, to do more.

39:02.773 --> 39:06.977 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They want it more -- to do more
in their lives
and to be more active.

39:07.078 --> 39:14.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this just goes completely
antithetical
to the Republican ideology of a
smaller, leaner,

39:14.985 --> 39:17.021 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
cheaper government withdrawing.

39:17.121 --> 39:19.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so, no, I think there's
great change in
the air.

39:19.657 --> 39:23.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't know where it comes
down, but it's
hard for me to see that there's
any hand on

39:23.728 --> 39:25.563 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the rudder of the ship of state.

39:25.663 --> 39:29.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But his
supporters -- and we
keep saying this in the polls,
and the reporters

39:29.533 --> 39:33.204 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who are going around the country
talking to
people who voted for Donald
Trump, David.

39:33.304 --> 39:34.205 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They still like what he's doing.

39:34.305 --> 39:35.206 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

39:35.306 --> 39:36.207 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
No, they do.

39:36.307 --> 39:37.208 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
People are solid.

39:37.308 --> 39:38.642 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
People are mostly driven by
partisanship.

39:38.743 --> 39:41.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The prism through which they see
reality is
their partisan identity.

39:41.679 --> 39:43.481 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so that will take some time
to shake off.

39:43.581 --> 39:45.249 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I do think it can be shaken off.

39:45.349 --> 39:48.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It seems very, very likely to me
this tax
reform is not going to go
anywhere, at least

39:49.053 --> 39:50.054 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
anything like its current form.

39:50.154 --> 39:51.922 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so how does he react to
that?

39:52.022 --> 39:55.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At what point does the economy
take a dip
and maybe people say, hey, what
exactly are

39:55.926 --> 39:57.161 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
you doing for me now?

39:57.261 --> 39:59.263 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I do think that will be a
while.

39:59.363 --> 40:04.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Partisan identity right now is
so strong that
if you ask people how is the
economy doing,

40:04.135 --> 40:05.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it doesn't matter how the
economy is doing.

40:05.903 --> 40:08.906 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It happens -- it's whether their
guy is in
power is how they see it.

40:09.006 --> 40:10.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, that loyalty will stay there
for a little
while.

40:11.041 --> 40:12.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Just one thing,
Judy.

40:13.010 --> 40:19.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And before Democrats start
popping the champagne,
67 percent of Americans feel
Democrats, the

40:19.483 --> 40:24.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Democratic Party, is out of
touch with what's
going on in their lives, more
than -- a lot

40:24.755 --> 40:27.091 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more than they feel that about
Donald Trump.

40:27.191 --> 40:34.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, if anything, yes, 96 to 98
percent of
the people who voted for him are
with him

40:34.131 --> 40:35.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and would do so again.

40:35.766 --> 40:40.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, I mean, the Democrats have
to be a lot
more than just, we're not Trump.

40:40.805 --> 40:42.306 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That is not the answer to their
problems.

40:42.406 --> 40:45.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It's not yet the
makings of
a comeback.

40:45.776 --> 40:47.278 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
MARK SHIELDS: No.

40:47.378 --> 40:50.581 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark Shields,
David Brooks,
we hope both of you come back.

40:50.681 --> 40:53.050 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

40:53.150 --> 40:57.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Oh, wow.

40:58.088 --> 40:59.857 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

40:59.957 --> 41:06.330 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Every day,
priceless cultural
objects around the world are
threatened by

41:06.430 --> 41:10.568 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
war, looting, the impact of
humans and the
passage of time.

41:10.668 --> 41:16.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But one organization in Spain is
taking an
innovative approach to
understanding and preserving

41:16.507 --> 41:19.443 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that heritage, by copying it.

41:19.543 --> 41:20.744 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has that story.

41:20.845 --> 41:24.448 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's part of our ongoing series
Culture at
Risk.

41:24.548 --> 41:31.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The tomb of Seti
I, ancient
Egyptian pharaoh, we watched it
being milled,

41:31.322 --> 41:33.858 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
printed, and set.

41:33.958 --> 41:40.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we're not in Egypt's Valley
of the Kings,
and certainly not in the 13th
century B.C.

41:40.197 --> 41:46.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is a workshop called Factum
Arte in an
eastern suburb of Madrid, Spain,
filled with

41:46.270 --> 41:51.775 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
art and historical works of all
kinds, with
one unusual thing in common.

41:51.876 --> 41:55.546 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Everything in this large
warehouse is a reproduction,
a copy.

41:55.646 --> 42:00.918 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the work that goes on here
raises profound
questions about just what is
real, and what

42:01.018 --> 42:02.620 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it means to preserve an object.

42:02.720 --> 42:05.122 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADAM LOWE, Factum Arte: We're
making copies
of copies.

42:05.222 --> 42:09.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The man who leads
Factum, with
evangelical fervor, is British
artist Adam

42:09.793 --> 42:11.529 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Lowe.

42:11.629 --> 42:15.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM LOWE: The state of the art
is that we
can make something that is
identical to the

42:16.000 --> 42:17.935 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
original, under normal viewing
conditions.

42:18.035 --> 42:22.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, is the idea
that you're
creating something that is, at
least for the

42:22.773 --> 42:26.310 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
viewing experience, as real as
the original?

42:26.410 --> 42:31.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM LOWE: The idea is that you
can get someone
to understand the complexity of
an object,

42:31.382 --> 42:35.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and you can get them to read it
in many ways
through encountering facsimile,
yes.

42:35.586 --> 42:39.957 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Facsimile, an
exact copy or
reproduction.

42:40.057 --> 42:45.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Factum calls its work digital
mediation, and
it operates as a kind of
renaissance workshop

42:45.262 --> 42:51.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of people with different skills:
software
designers, technicians,
conservators, architects,

42:51.535 --> 42:53.437 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
artists, artisans.

42:53.537 --> 42:59.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Together, they make copies with
a cause, not
to mislead, but to understand
and help preserve.

43:00.010 --> 43:04.214 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One prominent example, this copy
of a winged
lion from Nimrud.

43:04.315 --> 43:09.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was cast from sculptures now
in European
museums that were taken from the
site in Iraq

43:09.420 --> 43:11.488 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the 19 century.

43:11.589 --> 43:15.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Last year, ISIS destroyed much
of what's left
at Nimrud itself.

43:15.159 --> 43:21.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM LOWE: So, in that strange
twist of fate,
everything that was removed in
the 19th century

43:21.332 --> 43:23.601 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is the only evidence that's
left.

43:23.701 --> 43:29.773 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we would love to be able to
send facsimiles,
like this, back to Nimrud to
take up their

43:29.873 --> 43:33.911 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
place again on the site, so that
you still
keep that connection between...

43:34.011 --> 43:36.580 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: I mean, that
wouldn't make
up for the destruction, right?

43:36.680 --> 43:38.616 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ADAM LOWE: Nothing makes up for
destruction.

43:38.716 --> 43:44.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Factum first
attracted international
attention in 2007 by creating a
replica of

43:44.755 --> 43:51.028 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
a huge painting by Paolo
Veronese from 1563,
The Wedding at Cana.

43:51.128 --> 43:56.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The original painting now hangs
in the Louvre
museum in Paris, but it got
there as a gift

43:56.300 --> 44:01.805 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Napoleon, whose forces ripped
it from its
original home, a church in
Venice.

44:01.905 --> 44:07.745 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Factum's experts studied,
scanned, slowly
recreated it, and finally put
it, the copy,

44:07.845 --> 44:09.647 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that is, into its old home.

44:09.747 --> 44:14.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM LOWE: Many people started
to question
about whether the experience of
seeing it

44:14.818 --> 44:20.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in its correct setting, with the
correct light,
in dialogue with this building
that it was

44:20.190 --> 44:25.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
painted for, is actually more
authentic than
the experience of seeing the
original in the

44:25.396 --> 44:27.164 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Louvre.

44:27.264 --> 44:29.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Lowe had another
major win
in his recreation of King Tut's
tomb in the

44:29.900 --> 44:33.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Valley of the Kings, built next
to the original
site.

44:33.270 --> 44:37.174 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ADAM LOWE: It's a test between
one scanning
system.

44:37.274 --> 44:41.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: In Madrid, we got
a tour of
some key parts of the process,
which begins

44:41.879 --> 44:46.583 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
far away from this building,
with the scanning
of the actual objects in the
field.

44:46.684 --> 44:52.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That team is led by architect
Carlos Bayod,
using a laser scanner developed
at Factum

44:52.723 --> 44:54.425 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
known as the Lucida.

44:54.525 --> 44:57.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Â®MD-BO-CARLOS BAYOD, Factum
Arte: We are
capable now of recording the
surface of a

44:57.261 --> 45:03.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
painting, for example, and
obtaining data
that are very close, that has
very close correspondence

45:03.500 --> 45:04.401 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to reality.

45:04.501 --> 45:06.437 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: How close?

45:06.537 --> 45:09.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Â®MD-BO-CARLOS BAYOD: Well, in
terms of resolution,
we are talking about 100
microns, so one point

45:09.973 --> 45:11.909 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of information every 10th of a
millimeter.

45:12.009 --> 45:16.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The data about
the surface,
even of something we think of as
being flat,

45:16.914 --> 45:22.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is used to create a detailed
relief map of
the object, without ever
touching and potentially

45:22.419 --> 45:27.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
harming it, to understand how
any intervention
or restoration might play out.

45:27.658 --> 45:31.595 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Â®MD-BO-CARLOS BAYOD: We believe
this information
should be very useful for
conservators, people

45:31.695 --> 45:34.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who have the duty of taking care
of the works
of art.

45:34.965 --> 45:39.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: To go further and
build a facsimile
of the work, in this case the
tomb of Seti

45:39.903 --> 45:46.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I, the data is crunched and fed
into milling
machines, computer numeric code
routers, or

45:46.343 --> 45:48.545 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
3-D printers to create the
relief.

45:48.645 --> 45:54.451 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
In another room, using a
Factum-built printer
run by Rafa Rachewsky, the
photographed image

45:54.551 --> 45:57.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is etched onto a custom-created
surface known
as a skin.

45:58.055 --> 46:06.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAFA RACHEWSKY, Factum Arte: And
it's very
thin, as you can see.

46:06.697 --> 46:13.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It stretches enough so you can
lay it onto
the relief, and then you can
place exactly

46:13.470 --> 46:15.105 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
where you want.

46:15.205 --> 46:19.276 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Rachewsky
carefully aligns
the printed skin with the
relief, and using

46:19.376 --> 46:20.677 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
contact glue:

46:20.778 --> 46:22.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAFA RACHEWSKY: You want to be
sure that you
get everywhere.

46:22.513 --> 46:25.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Because you want
it to hold
for several thousand years,
right?

46:25.816 --> 46:26.717 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:26.817 --> 46:27.718 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RAFA RACHEWSKY: Exactly.

46:27.818 --> 46:29.353 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: It's then
vacuum-sealed.

46:29.453 --> 46:35.859 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAFA RACHEWSKY: As the air is
coming out,
these two are joining together.

46:35.959 --> 46:39.496 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, now it's
really fusing
into one.

46:39.596 --> 46:41.298 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RAFA RACHEWSKY: Exactly.

46:41.398 --> 46:46.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The result, a
test panel of
the tomb of Seti I, representing
less than

46:46.403 --> 46:51.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
1 percent of what will be a
full-scale replica,
to eventually go on display next
to the original

46:51.942 --> 46:53.377 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in Luxor.

46:53.477 --> 46:55.612 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And why build a replica of the
tomb?

46:55.712 --> 47:01.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because, says Adam Lowe, mass
tourism, our
own need to see the original in
a place never

47:01.718 --> 47:05.022 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
designed for our biological
presence, has
its consequences.

47:05.122 --> 47:12.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM LOWE: But what we're really
asking the
visitors to do is to enter into
a new contract

47:12.162 --> 47:17.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for preserving things for the
future, because
by going to see something that
was designed

47:17.134 --> 47:21.972 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to last for eternity, but never
to be visited,
you're contributing to its
destruction.

47:22.072 --> 47:26.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This is expensive
work, developing
new tools and techniques to take
on whatever

47:27.077 --> 47:31.315 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
challenges the world of
conservation throws
at it.

47:31.415 --> 47:35.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
To finance it, Factum builds
custom pieces
for contemporary artists, like
this piece

47:35.819 --> 47:40.891 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
for Saudi Arabian artist
Abdulnasser Gharem,
which combines the dome of a
mosque with a

47:40.991 --> 47:46.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
soldier's helmet, and will be
installed at
the Los Angeles County Museum of
Art.

47:46.797 --> 47:51.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Factum is full of wonders, not
the least of
which was getting into a
contraption built

47:51.468 --> 48:01.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
here called a Veronica scanner,
12 cameras
taking 96 high-resolution photos
of all angles

48:01.345 --> 48:04.147 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of my head in four seconds.

48:04.248 --> 48:08.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
After an hour-and-a-half of 3-D
printing,
my very own small bust.

48:08.919 --> 48:10.821 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Oh, my goodness.

48:10.921 --> 48:16.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As technology advances and laser
scans are
increasingly replaced by this
kind of photogrammetry,

48:16.927 --> 48:21.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's not hard to imagine a world
in which
anyone can photograph an object
and render

48:21.531 --> 48:23.267 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
their own model in 3-D.

48:23.367 --> 48:27.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM LOWE: But I can imagine
many things,
so I can imagine I can take a
photograph,

48:27.604 --> 48:31.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as we're doing, and I could
recreate something
from a photograph.

48:31.208 --> 48:36.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I can imagine other people might
do it for
less noble reasons or for
straightforward

48:36.613 --> 48:39.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
commercial reasons, but that's
not a reason
for not doing it.

48:39.549 --> 48:44.388 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The recording critical, because
unless you
record it, you don't know how
it's changing,

48:44.488 --> 48:49.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you don't know what people's
presence is going
to it, you don't know the
effects of time

48:49.593 --> 48:51.428 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on the surface.

48:51.528 --> 48:55.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: While Adam Lowe
is most focused
now on pushing conservation
techniques, he's

48:55.299 --> 49:00.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
also challenging how we think
about copies
and their relationship to
originals, the very

49:00.437 --> 49:02.873 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
idea of originality.

49:02.973 --> 49:07.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The classical sculptures we
know, he points
out, are almost all copies of an
original.

49:07.978 --> 49:10.647 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And all those masterpiece
paintings we love?

49:10.747 --> 49:14.751 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ADAM LOWE: You go to the
National Gallery
in London, you go to the
National Gallery

49:14.851 --> 49:18.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Washington, and every single
one of those
paintings has a complex history.

49:19.022 --> 49:20.991 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's probably restored once or
twice.

49:21.091 --> 49:26.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's probably had more than that
by certain
dubious dealers who've tarted it
up to sell

49:26.363 --> 49:28.098 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

49:28.198 --> 49:30.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, there's a whole history of
what happens
on a painting that's constantly
changing.

49:30.634 --> 49:34.171 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: There's no
original when it
comes to a work of art, you're
suggesting.

49:34.271 --> 49:39.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ADAM LOWE: No, I'm suggesting
there is seldom
a very clear notion of
conception.

49:39.276 --> 49:43.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The way we see and understand
cultural heritage
changes over time.

49:43.347 --> 49:45.682 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It always has, and it always
will.

49:45.782 --> 49:50.454 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the way we value it, the way
we look at
it, the way we appreciate it,
the way we display

49:50.554 --> 49:55.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it, the way we collect it, all
of these things
are constantly subject to
change.

49:55.993 --> 50:02.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A change at
Factum Arte's workshop
happening before our eyes.

50:02.332 --> 50:13.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Jeffrey Brown
in Madrid, Spain.

50:13.543 --> 50:26.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: One of the core
tenets of the
American dream is the belief
that any individual,

50:26.690 --> 50:30.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
regardless of their background,
can make it
big.

50:30.160 --> 50:35.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Millionaire tech entrepreneur
Jason Ford has
done just that, but he believes
that he and

50:35.132 --> 50:39.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
other successful people get a
lot of help
they don't often acknowledge.

50:39.703 --> 50:43.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He explains in tonight's edition
of In My
Humble Opinion.

50:43.140 --> 50:46.877 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JASON FORD, Entrepreneur:
Everyone loves a
good success story.

50:46.977 --> 50:51.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's the American dream, working
your way
up from nothing, armed only with
your wits

50:51.782 --> 50:53.717 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and a strong work ethic.

50:53.817 --> 50:57.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And for those who make it, it
feels great
to think you got there all on
your own.

50:57.788 --> 51:03.493 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I should know: I'm a
millionaire, the first
in my family, one of those tech
entrepreneurs

51:03.593 --> 51:06.496 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who built a software business
and sold it
for a fortune.

51:06.596 --> 51:07.964 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I didn't inherit my wealth.

51:08.065 --> 51:09.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I created it.

51:09.900 --> 51:15.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But look a little deeper, and it
turns out
that version of my success story
is a lie.

51:15.705 --> 51:18.809 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Yes, my family background is
rather humble.

51:18.909 --> 51:20.010 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Both of my parents were
teachers.

51:20.110 --> 51:22.712 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I grew up in hand-me-down
clothes from our
neighbors.

51:22.813 --> 51:28.952 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, before I was born, my
parents got help
from their parents to buy a
house in a safe

51:29.052 --> 51:31.621 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
neighborhood with good schools.

51:31.721 --> 51:36.393 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When my grandmother passed, she
left each
of her grandkids some money, not
a fortune,

51:36.493 --> 51:39.396 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
but enough that I made it
through college
without school debt.

51:39.496 --> 51:41.998 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
My wife's nana was a school
teacher as well.

51:42.099 --> 51:47.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She and her husband saved their
humble income
and bought land decades ago.

51:47.137 --> 51:52.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when I started my business,
she believed
in me enough to sell her land
and invest the

51:52.209 --> 51:53.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
money in my start-up.

51:53.477 --> 51:57.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, we can blow up the myth that
I'm a self-made
success.

51:57.447 --> 52:02.352 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sure, I had something to do with
it, but I
also had some serious help.

52:02.452 --> 52:08.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, one way to interpret this
story is that
the generations before me worked
hard to provide

52:08.492 --> 52:11.094 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the best possible future for
their kids and
grandkids.

52:11.194 --> 52:18.135 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that interpretation is true,
but it leaves
out some harsh realities rooted
in history.

52:18.235 --> 52:23.306 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You see, if my ancestors had not
been white,
it is almost certain that I
wouldn't be where

52:23.406 --> 52:25.175 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I am today.

52:25.275 --> 52:28.345 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My grandfather would have found
it nearly
impossible to climb to the top
of the corporate

52:28.445 --> 52:30.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ladder like he did.

52:30.313 --> 52:35.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This was the mid-'70s, when
almost every executive
in a role like his was a white
man.

52:35.152 --> 52:39.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As a result, my parents likely
wouldn't have
bought the House They did, with
the good schools

52:39.723 --> 52:41.591 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that prepared me for college.

52:41.691 --> 52:46.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And two generations ago, lending
discrimination
would have made it similarly
impossible for

52:46.696 --> 52:52.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nana to buy that land that ended
up funding
my business.

52:52.169 --> 52:56.306 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Just as not everyone is
qualified to be an
astronaut, it takes a special
kind of person

52:56.406 --> 52:57.607 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to be an entrepreneur.

52:57.707 --> 53:01.678 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You need discipline,
intelligence, extreme
dedication.

53:01.778 --> 53:07.217 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the best astronaut in the
world can't
fly to the moon unless someone
gives them

53:07.317 --> 53:09.052 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the rocket.

53:09.152 --> 53:13.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's time for more entrepreneurs
like me to
stop telling stories about how
they climbed

53:13.390 --> 53:18.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their way to the top, to stop
taking credit
for flying to the moon all by
themselves,

53:18.395 --> 53:23.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
as if the entire support
structure they were
born into had nothing to do with
it.

53:23.700 --> 53:29.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's time for all of us to
find more ways
to empower the world's
highest-potential entrepreneurs

53:29.472 --> 53:33.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with their own rockets, so they
can show us
the stars.

53:33.543 --> 53:36.079 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Something to
think about.

53:36.179 --> 53:39.716 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Robert Costa is getting
ready for "Washington
Week" later this evening.

53:39.816 --> 53:41.685 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
